{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-04-01T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Today, let's hop into the world of one of nature's smallest yet most hardworking ambassadors. Frogs may not wear crowns—unless you believe in Frog Kings—but they do rule quietly behind the scenes. By keeping insect populations in check, they help ecosystems stay balanced. Even more impressive? Their sensitive skin also means they react quickly to changes in their surroundings, which is why scientists often look at frogs to understand the health of wetlands and forests. Talk about living barometers.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.JapaneseTreeFrog_EN-CA4832337394_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.JapaneseTreeFrog_EN-CA4832337394_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Hopping into April","Title":"Japanese tree frog in a pink morning glory","Copyright":"© Tetsuya Tanooka/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"The oldest known 'proto-frog,' Triadobatrachus massinoti, lived about 250 million years ago during the Early Triassic period.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260401_JapaneseTreeFrog\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Japanese+tree+frog&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260401_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260401_JapaneseTreeFrog"},"Ssd":"20260401","Name":"JapaneseTreeFrog","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"4832337394","FullDateString":"Apr. 1, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Paradise Cave makes a powerful first impression the moment visitors step inside. This vast limestone cavern lies deep within Phong Nha-Ke Bang National Park in central Vietnam, a region marked by rugged mountains and countless hidden caves. Stretching 31 kilometres, Paradise Cave is one of Asia's longest dry caves, and its scale is immediately apparent. High ceilings rise above the walkways and layered patterns formed by mineral-rich water over millions of years line the walls.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ParadiseCave_EN-CA4527234429_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ParadiseCave_EN-CA4527234429_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Underground paradise","Title":"Paradise Cave, Phong Nha-Ke Bang National Park, Vietnam","Copyright":"© Pakawat Thongcharoen/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/16.835573,106.743552/3?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-CA&od=2&shading=flat&pp=16.835573,106.743552;S9;Paradise Cave, Phong Nha-Ke Bang National Park, Vietnam&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260331_ParadiseCave\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Paradise+Cave+Vietnam&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260331_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260331_ParadiseCave"},"Ssd":"20260331","Name":"ParadiseCave","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"4527234429","FullDateString":"Mar. 31, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The demoiselle crane is a small yet striking migratory bird found across Central Asia, from its breeding grounds in the steppes of Kazakhstan, Mongolia and northern China, to its wintering grounds in India, Nepal and parts of Africa. With its elegant appearance—slender neck, long legs and beautiful plumage—it is often considered one of the most graceful crane species. They are known for their intricate courtship dances, during which pairs engage in synchronised movements and calls, creating a beautiful spectacle.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.IndiaCranes_EN-CA7425221513_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.IndiaCranes_EN-CA7425221513_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Elegance in motion","Title":"Demoiselle cranes, India","Copyright":"© Axel Gomille/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"In North India, the demoiselle crane is called 'koonj' and is a symbol of grace and beauty in literature.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260330_IndiaCranes\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Demoiselle+cranes&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260330_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260330_IndiaCranes"},"Ssd":"20260330","Name":"IndiaCranes","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"7425221513","FullDateString":"Mar. 30, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Peggy's Cove is a small yet captivating village on the rugged coast of Nova Scotia that offers a glimpse of life by the sea. The village's most famous landmark is Peggy's Point Lighthouse—also known as Peggy's Cove Lighthouse—first established in 1868 and replaced by the current structure in 1915. For over a century, it has guided ships through the ever-changing Atlantic waters, serving as a timeless symbol of coastal life. The surrounding landscape, with its windswept beauty and crashing waves, feels almost untouched by time.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PeggysLighthouse_EN-CA3906475667_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PeggysLighthouse_EN-CA3906475667_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Serenity by the sea","Title":"Peggy's Point Lighthouse, Atlantic Coast, Nova Scotia","Copyright":"© Prashanth Bala/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/44.492264,-63.918158/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-CA&od=2&shading=flat&pp=44.492264,-63.918158;S9;Peggy's Point Lighthouse, Atlantic Coast, Nova Scotia&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260329_PeggysLighthouse\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Peggys+Point+Lighthouse&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260329_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260329_PeggysLighthouse"},"Ssd":"20260329","Name":"PeggysLighthouse","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"3906475667","FullDateString":"Mar. 29, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The African buffalo, a powerful and imposing creature, roams the savannas and wetlands of Tanzania, particularly within the Ngorongoro Conservation Area (NCA). Known for their large, curved horns and massive size, they are one of Africa's 'Big Five' (buffalo, elephant, leopard, rhino, lion) and are widely respected for their strength and resilience. The NCA, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, offers a dramatic and ecologically rich setting for observing these formidable herbivores.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.CapeBuffalo_EN-CA3514902846_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.CapeBuffalo_EN-CA3514902846_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"The untamed spirit","Title":"African buffalo, Ngorongoro Crater, Tanzania","Copyright":"© jesuss8/500px/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/-3.064646,35.381698/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-CA&od=2&shading=flat&pp=-3.064646,35.381698;S9;Ngorongoro Crater, Tanzania&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260328_CapeBuffalo\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=African+buffalo&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260328_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260328_CapeBuffalo"},"Ssd":"20260328","Name":"CapeBuffalo","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"3514902846","FullDateString":"Mar. 28, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"At first glance, there's no doubt that the interior of Radio City Music Hall pulls you in and cranks up the excitement. It feels like stepping straight into the sun in the middle of New York City—an Art Deco fever dream of how the 1930s imagined the future. This rush of awe is celebrated every March 27 as World Theatre Day.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.RadioCityHall_EN-CA3187360492_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.RadioCityHall_EN-CA3187360492_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":false},"Headline":"Still burning bright","Title":"Radio City Music Hall in New York City, United States","Copyright":"© Clarence Holmes Photography/Alamy","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/40.759968,-73.979912/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-CA&od=2&shading=flat&pp=40.759968,-73.979912;S9;Radio City Music Hall, New York City, United States&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260327_RadioCityHall\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=World+Theatre+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260327_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260327_RadioCityHall"},"Ssd":"20260327","Name":"RadioCityHall","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"3187360492","FullDateString":"Mar. 27, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Running along the remote southwest coast of Vancouver Island, the West Coast Trail is one of the country's most legendary hikes. Located in British Columbia's Pacific Rim National Park Reserve, the trail stretches about 76 kilometres through rainforest, beaches and rocky shoreline. It was established in 1907 as a lifesaving route for shipwreck survivors along what sailors once called the 'Graveyard of the Pacific.'","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.LoganCreek_EN-CA2859190085_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.LoganCreek_EN-CA2859190085_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"A step above the wild","Title":"Logan Creek Suspension Bridge, West Coast Trail, British Columbia","Copyright":"© Tandem Stock/Adobe Stock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"The West Coast Trail typically takes 6 to 8 days to complete, due to mud, ladders, rivers and harsh coastal weather.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260326_LoganCreek\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=West+Coast+Trail+hike&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260326_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260326_LoganCreek"},"Ssd":"20260326","Name":"LoganCreek","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"2859190085","FullDateString":"Mar. 26, 2026"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Seattle's waterfront seems suspended between sea and sky as soft light settles on the horizon. The city is named after Chief Si'ahl, a leader of the Duwamish and Suquamish peoples, whose legacy remains important to the region's identity. Steep streets lead down to piers that sweep across Elliott Bay. Rising above the shoreline, the Space Needle stands out as the city's most recognisable landmark. Pike Place Market, founded in 1907, overlooks the waterfront and continues to anchor daily life and long-held traditions.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SeattleSunrise_EN-CA2571185847_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SeattleSunrise_EN-CA2571185847_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"The Emerald City","Title":"Seattle, Washington, United States","Copyright":"© Jim Patterson/Tandem Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/47.60323,-122.330276/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-CA&od=2&shading=flat&pp=47.60323,-122.330276;S9;Seattle, Washington, United States&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260408_SeattleSunrise\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Seattle&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260408_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260408_SeattleSunrise"},"Ssd":"20260408","Name":"SeattleSunrise","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"2571185847","FullDateString":"Apr. 8, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"International Beaver Day, celebrated on April 7, recognises a hardworking little engineer quietly building a better world—one stick at a time. The beaver—buck-toothed, paddle-tailed and famously industrious—has been reshaping freshwater landscapes for millions of years. With their iron-reinforced orange incisors, these skilled rodents cut down trees and build dams that slow the flow of water, improve its quality and create wetlands that support a remarkable diversity of life. Their sturdy lodges, made of branches and mud, have underwater entrances that protect them from predators and keep their families safe.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BeaverPortrait_EN-CA2325425588_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BeaverPortrait_EN-CA2325425588_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"One stick at a time","Title":"Beaver, Germany","Copyright":"© Andyworks/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"Beavers' orange teeth contain iron in their enamel, which makes their incisors tougher and more resistant to wear than human teeth enamel.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260407_BeaverPortrait\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Beaver+rodent&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260407_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260407_BeaverPortrait"},"Ssd":"20260407","Name":"BeaverPortrait","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"2325425588","FullDateString":"Apr. 7, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Picture northern Japan in the early 1600s. Castles stood at the crossroads of politics, trade and governance. Across generations, they came to reflect not only moments of tension, but also endurance, adaptation and everyday life. Castle Day, celebrated on April 6, was created to highlight that layered past. The day uses a simple phonetic link—shi (4) and ro (6)—to form Shiro-no-Hi, because 'shiro' means castle in Japanese. It's a reminder that castles had serious jobs long before they had cinematic appeal.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.CastleBlossoms_EN-CA1798513308_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.CastleBlossoms_EN-CA1798513308_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Where power resides","Title":"Hirosaki Castle with cherry blossoms, Hirosaki, Japan","Copyright":"© Glenn Waters/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/40.609463,140.467545/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-CA&od=2&shading=flat&pp=40.609463,140.467545;S9;Hirosaki Castle, Hirosaki, Japan&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260406_CastleBlossoms\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Japanese+castle&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260406_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260406_CastleBlossoms"},"Ssd":"20260406","Name":"CastleBlossoms","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"1798513308","FullDateString":"Apr. 6, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"What follows 40 days of waiting is not a spectacle, but a chapter rooted in belief. Easter Sunday arrives at the end of Lent, carrying forward ideas of life over death and the promise of renewal. For Christians, today marks the resurrection of Jesus Christ and brings Holy Week to a close. It's a turning point, both spiritual and symbolic.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.LithuaniaEggs_EN-CA1968475301_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.LithuaniaEggs_EN-CA1968475301_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Hello, Easter Sunday","Title":"Colourful handmade wooden Easter eggs, Vilnius, Lithuania","Copyright":"© maximkabb/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"Easter Sunday marks the end of the 40-day Lenten season of fasting, prayer and penance.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260405_LithuaniaEggs\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Easter+Sunday&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260405_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260405_LithuaniaEggs"},"Ssd":"20260405","Name":"LithuaniaEggs","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"1968475301","FullDateString":"Apr. 5, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Before sunrise, the moorland clock punches in—and the dance floor opens. Male black grouse don't send invites; they boom them. Welcome to lekking season, where romance is competitive, noisy and strictly outdoors.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.GrouseGuff_EN-CA6763957448_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.GrouseGuff_EN-CA6763957448_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"The lek side story","Title":"Black grouse males facing off on a lekking site, Estonia","Copyright":"© Sven Zacek/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"Black grouse males have a striking, bright red wattle (skin) above their eyes, which they inflate during mating displays.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260404_GrouseGuff\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Black+grouse&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260404_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260404_GrouseGuff"},"Ssd":"20260404","Name":"GrouseGuff","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"6763957448","FullDateString":"Apr. 4, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Some bridges in Amsterdam just get you across a canal. The Armbrug does more—it seems to wave hello as you pass. Nestled over the Oudezijds Voorburgwal canal, its name, meaning 'arm bridge,' refers to the nearby Oudezijds Armsteeg (Old Side Arm Alley), not a literal limb, but it's easy to imagine it greeting cyclists and pedestrians along the way.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ArmbrugBridge_EN-CA6719297675_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ArmbrugBridge_EN-CA6719297675_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Bridging the gap, one arm at a time","Title":"Armbrug bridge, Amsterdam, Netherlands","Copyright":"© Alexander Spatari/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/52.375378,4.900051/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-CA&od=2&shading=flat&pp=52.375378,4.900051;S9;Oudezijds Armsteeg & Oudezijds Voorburgwal Canal Bridge, Netherlands&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260403_ArmbrugBridge\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Armbrug+bridge+Amsterdam&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260403_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260403_ArmbrugBridge"},"Ssd":"20260403","Name":"ArmbrugBridge","Market":"EN-CA","Hash":"6719297675","FullDateString":"Apr. 3, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Spring announces itself across California's Central Valley with the first bursts of wildflowers following the winter rains. Stretching about 720 kilometres from north to south and covering approximately 51,800 square kilometres, the valley is one of the world's most productive agricultural regions. In early spring, however, an older identity briefly resurfaces. From March through April, native annuals such as goldfields, tidy tips and owl's clover quickly germinate once temperature and soil moisture are optimal. They race to complete their life cycles before the long dry season begins.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.WildflowerValley_EN-CA5205263100_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.WildflowerValley_EN-CA5205263100_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Patterns of spring","Title":"Wildflower bloom, Central Valley, California, United States","Copyright":"© Jeff Lewis/Tandem Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/40.522843,-122.240585/3?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-CA&od=2&shading=flat&pp=40.522843,-122.240585;S9;Central Valley, California, United States&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260402_WildflowerValley\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Central+Valley+California&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260402_0400\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\""